{"title_page": "Health in Belgium", "text_new": "A new measure of expected [[human capital]] calculated for 195 countries from 1990 to 2016 and defined for each birth cohort as the expected years lived from age 20 to 64 years and adjusted for educational attainment, learning or education quality, and functional health status was published by the [[The Lancet|Lancet]] in September 2018. Belgium had the tenth highest level of expected human capital with 25 health, education, and learning-adjusted expected years lived between age 20 and 64 years. <ref>{{cite news |last1=Lim |first1=Stephen |last2=et |first2=al |title=Measuring human capital: a systematic analysis of 195 countries and territories, 1990\u20132016 |url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(18)31941-X/fulltext |accessdate=5 November 2018 |publisher=Lancet}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Healthcare in Belgium]]\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Europe in topic|Health in}}\n\n[[Category:Health in Belgium| ]]\n", "text_old": "A new measure of expected [[human capital]] calculated for 195 countries from 1990 to 2016 and defined for each birth cohort as the expected years lived from age 20 to 64 years and adjusted for educational attainment, learning or education quality, and functional health status was published by the [[The Lancet|Lancet]] in September 2018. Belgium had the tenth highest level of expected human capital with 25 health, education, and learning-adjusted expected years lived between age 20 and 64 years. <ref>{{cite news |last1=Lim |first1=Stephen |last2=et |first2=al |title=Measuring human capital: a systematic analysis of 195 countries and territories, 1990\u20132016 |url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(18)31941-X/fulltext |accessdate=5 November 2018 |publisher=Lancet}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n[[Healthcare in Belgium]]\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Europe in topic|Health in}}\n\n[[Category:Health in Belgium| ]]\n", "name_user": "Chongkian", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Health_in_Belgium"}
{"title_page": "TC Energy", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian energy company}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = TC Energy Corporation\n| logo = TC Energy Logo May 2019.svg\n| image = TransCanapr20.JPG\n| image_size = 150px\n| image_caption = [[TransCanada Tower]], the company's head office in Calgary\n| type = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as = {{Plainlist|\n* {{TSX|TRP}}\n* [[S&P/TSX 60|S&P/TSX 60 component]]}}\n| industry = [[Energy industry|Energy]]\n| founder = \n| defunct = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| hq_location = [[TransCanada Tower]]\n| hq_location_city = [[Calgary]], [[Alberta]]\n| hq_location_country = Canada\n| area_served = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Canada]]\n* [[Mexico]]\n* [[United States]]}}\n| key_people = [[Russ Girling]], President and CEO\n| production = \n| services = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Pipeline transport]]\n* [[Natural gas storage]]\n* [[Electricity generation]]}} \n| revenue = {{increase}} [[C$]]13.68 billion (2018)<ref name=\"2018 Annual Report\">{{cite report |url=https://www.tcenergy.com/globalassets/pdfs/investors/tc-annual-report.pdf |date=2019 |title=Annual Report 2018 |access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n| net_income = {{increase}} [[C$]]3.54 billion (2018)<ref name=\"2018 Annual Report\"/>\n| assets = {{increase}} [[C$]]98.92 billion (2018)<ref name=\"2018 Annual Report\"/>\n| equity = {{increase}} [[C$]]25.36 billion (2018)<ref name=\"2018 Annual Report\"/>\n| num_employees = 7,000<ref name= \"Energy and Commitment\">{{cite |url=https://www.tcenergy.com/globalassets/pdfs/media/fact-sheets/tc-our-business-at-a-glance.pdf |work=TC Energy |title=Fact sheet}}</ref>\n| foundation = 1951\n| locations = <!-- Number of locations, stores, offices, etc. -->\n| homepage = {{URL|https://www.tcenergy.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''TC Energy Corporation''' (formerly '''TransCanada Corporation''') is a major North American [[energy company]], based in [[Calgary]], [[Alberta]], Canada, that develops and operates energy infrastructure in Canada, the United States, and Mexico. The company operates three core businesses: Natural Gas Pipelines, Liquids Pipelines and Energy.\n\nThe Natural Gas Pipeline network includes {{convert|92,600|km|mi|0|abbr=off}} of [[gas pipeline]], which transports more than 25% of North American natural gas demand. The Liquids Pipelines division includes {{convert|4,900|km|mi|0|abbr=off}} of oil pipeline, which ships 590,000 barrels of crude oil per day, which is about 20% of Western Canadian exports. The Energy division owns or has interests in 11 power generation facilities with combined capacity of 6,600 megawatts (MW). These power sources include nuclear and natural gas fired.<ref name=\"2018 Annual Report\"/>\n\nThe company was founded in 1951 in Calgary.<ref>{{cite book |first=William |last=Kilbourn|authorlink=William Kilbourn |year=1970 |title=Pipeline: TransCanada and the Great Debate |url=https://archive.org/details/pipelinetranscan00kilb |url-access=registration | page= [https://archive.org/details/pipelinetranscan00kilb/page/29 29]}}</ref> TC Energy is the largest [[shareholder]] in, and owns the [[general partner]] of, [[TC PipeLines]].\n\n==History==\nThe company was incorporated in 1951 by a Special Act of Parliament as Trans-Canada Pipe Lines Limited.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fundinguniverse.com/company-histories/transcanada-pipelines-limited-history/|title=History of TRANSCANADA PIPELINES LIMITED \u2013 FundingUniverse|website=www.fundinguniverse.com|language=en|access-date=2018-03-13}}</ref> The purpose of the company was to develop the [[TransCanada pipeline]] (now known as the Canadian Mainline) to supply eastern Canadian markets with natural gas produced in the west.\n\nIn 1998, TransCanada Pipelines merged with [[NOVA Corporation]]'s pipeline business, keeping the TransCanada name and becoming \"the fourth largest energy services company in North America\".<ref name=\"Merger\">{{Cite web |title=TransCanada, Nova Complete Merger |url=https://www.naturalgasintel.com/articles/92796-transcanada-nova-complete-merger |publisher=Natural Gas Intellicence |date=1998-07-06 |accessdate=2020-03-01}}</ref>\n\n[[File:TransCanada Logo.svg|thumb|Logo of TransCanada before rebranding as TC Energy in 2019|alt=]]\n\nSeeking to expand its presence in the United States, in 2016, TransCanada acquired Columbia Pipeline Group for US$13 billion. The Columbia acquisition added a pipeline network in Pennsylvania and surrounding states, where the [[Marcellus Formation|Marcellus]] and [[Utica Shale|Utica]] shale gas formations are located.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://business.financialpost.com/commodities/energy/transcanada-corp-to-acquire-columbia-pipeline-group-in-us13-billion-deal|title=TransCanada Corp to overhaul its business in US$13B acquisition of Columbia Pipeline Group|date=2016-03-18|work=Financial Post|access-date=2018-03-15|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, the company changed its name from TransCanada Corporation to TC Energy Corporation to better reflect the company's business, which includes pipelines, power generation and energy storage operations in Canada, the United States and Mexico.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-transcanada-results-idUSKCN1S911H|title=Pipeline company TransCanada changes name to TC Energy|last=Williams|first=Nia|date=2019-05-03|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-05-05|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://o.canada.com/commodities/not-a-brand-change-new-name-same-pipeline-challenges-for-tc-energy/wcm/65c5dc2d-2f5b-4664-be29-64b476d129de|title=\u2018Not a brand change\u2019: New name, same pipeline challenges for TC Energy|date=2019-05-03|website=canada.com|language=en-ca|access-date=2019-05-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.commondreams.org/news/2019/05/04/transcanada-can-change-its-name-say-opponents-keystone-xl-will-never-see-light-day|title=TransCanada Can Change Its Name, Say Opponents, But Keystone XL Will Never See 'The Light of Day'|last=Queally|first=Jon|date=2019-05-04|website=Common Dreams|language=en|access-date=2019-05-05}}</ref>\n\n==Operations==\n===Natural gas pipelines===\nTC Energy's natural gas pipelines business builds, owns and operates a network of natural gas pipelines across North America that connects gas production to interconnects and end use markets. The company transports over 25% of continental daily natural gas demand through 91,900&nbsp;km (57,100&nbsp;mi) of pipelines. In addition, the company owns 535 Bcf of natural gas storage facilities, making TC Energy one of the largest natural gas storage providers in North America. This segment is TC Energy's largest segment, generating approximately two-thirds of the company's [[EBITDA]] in 2017. The Natural Gas Pipelines business is split into three operating segments: Canadian Natural Gas Pipelines, U.S. Natural Gas Pipelines, and Mexico Natural Gas Pipelines.<ref name=\"2018 Annual Report\"/>\n\nThe major pipeline systems include:\n\n*'''NGTL System (24,320&nbsp;km)''' A wholly-owned subsidiary, NOVA Gas Transmission Ltd., connects gas producers in the [[Western Canadian Sedimentary Basin]] with consumers and exports.<ref>{{Cite web |title=NGTL System |url=https://www.tcenergy.com/operations/natural-gas/ngtl-system/ |publisher=TC Energy |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309000228/https://www.tcenergy.com/operations/natural-gas/ngtl-system/ |archivedate=2020-03-09|accessdate=2020-03-09}}</ref> TC Energy has the largest and most extensive natural gas network in Alberta.<ref name=pri>{{cite news|title=TransCanada rule change raises ire of producers|agency=Financial Post|last=Morgan|first=Geoffrey|newspaper=Saskatchewan StarPhoenix|url=https://www.pressreader.com/canada/saskatoon-starphoenix/20171101/282226600986366|date=November 1, 2017}}</ref>\n*'''[[TransCanada pipeline|Canadian Mainline]] (14,077&nbsp;km)''' this pipeline serves as a long haul delivery system transporting natural gas from the [[Western Canadian Sedimentary Basin]] across Canada to Ontario and Qu\u00e9bec to deliver gas to downstream Canadian and U.S. markets. The pipeline has evolved accommodate additional supply connections closer to its markets. The mainline is over 60 years old <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.transcanada.com/en/operations/natural-gas/canadian-mainline/|title=TransCanada Canadian Mainline \u2013 Overview|author=|date=|website=www.transcanada.com}}</ref>\n*'''[[Columbia Gas Transmission|Columbia Gas]] (18,113&nbsp;km)''' This natural gas transportation system serves the [[Appalachian Basin]], which contains the [[Marcellus Formation|Marcellus]] and [[Utica Shale|Utica]] plays, two of the largest natural gas shale plays in North America. The system also interconnects with other pipelines that provide access to the U.S. Northeast and the Gulf of Mexico.'''\n*'''[[ANR Pipeline|ANR Pipeline System]] (15,109&nbsp;km)''' This pipeline system connects supply basins and markets throughout the U.S. Midwest, and south to the Gulf of Mexico. This includes connecting supply in Texas, Oklahoma, the Appalachian Basin and the Gulf of Mexico to markets in Wisconsin, Michigan, Illinois and Ohio. In addition, ANR has bi-directional capability on its Southeast Mainline and delivers gas produced from the Appalachian basin to customers throughout the Gulf Coast Region.\n*'''[[Columbia Gulf Transmission|Columbia Gulf]] (5,377&nbsp;km)''' \u2013 This pipeline system was originally designed as a long haul delivery system transporting supply from the Gulf of Mexico to major demand markets in the U.S. Northeast. The pipeline is now transitioning to a north-to-south flow and expanding to accommodate new supply in the Appalachian Basin and its interconnects with Columbia Gas and other pipelines to deliver gas to various Gulf Coast markets.\n*'''Mexico Pipeline Network (1,680&nbsp;km)''' \u2013 This consists of a growing network of natural gas pipelines in Mexico.\n\nProjects in development include:\n\n'''[[Coastal GasLink Pipeline|Coastal GasLink Pipeline Project]]''' \u2013 In June 2012 it was announced that TransCanada was selected by Shell and [[LNG Canada]] partners [[Korea Gas Corporation]], [[Mitsubishi]] Corporation and [[PetroChina]] Company Limited (to which [[Petronas]] of Malaysia was added in 2018) to design, build, own and operate<ref name=TC6512>{{cite news|title=TransCanada Selected by Shell and Partners to Develop Multi-Billion Dollar Natural Gas Pipeline to Canada's West Coast|url=http://www.transcanada.com/6054.html|accessdate=June 12, 2013|newspaper=TransCanada|date=June 5, 2012|format=news release}}</ref> the Coastal GasLink pipeline between northeastern B.C. gas fields near [[Dawson Creek, British Columbia]], and the [[LNG Canada]] LNG liquefaction, storage and export facility in the port of [[Kitimat]], on the [[Douglas Channel]].<ref name=Tyee01913>{{cite news|title=TransCanada to build $5-billion shale gas pipeline project near Prince Rupert|url=https://thetyee.ca/Blogs/TheHook/2013/01/09/TransCanada-Shale-Project/|accessdate=June 12, 2013|newspaper=The Tyee|date=January 9, 2013|last=Krugel|first=Lauren|format=blog}}</ref><ref name=HomeCoastal>{{cite web|title=Home page|url=http://www.coastalgaslink.com/|publisher=Coastal GasLink Pipeline Ltd., a wholly owned subsidiary of TransCanada PipeLines Limited|accessdate=June 12, 2013|quote=Coastal GasLink Pipeline Ltd., a wholly owned subsidiary of TransCanada PipeLines Limited, proposes to develop a natural gas pipeline from northeast B.C. to the west coast of B.C. to serve export markets.}}</ref><ref name = ProjectDescription >[http://www.coastalgaslink.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/Coastal-GasLink-Project-Description-Nov-07_12.pdf Coastal GasLink Pipeline project description]</ref><ref name=GM6512>{{cite news|title=TransCanada wins $4-billion pipeline contract|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/industry-news/energy-and-resources/transcanada-wins-4-billion-pipeline-contract/article4231488/|accessdate=June 12, 2013|newspaper=The Globe and Mail|date=June 5, 2012|author=Nathan VanderKlippe}}</ref>\nThe investment and construction decisions for the [[LNG Canada]] and Coastal GasLink Pipeline Project were officially confirmed early October 2018, for completion by 2024-2025. However, hereditary chiefs of the [[Wet\u02bcsuwet\u02bcen]] have denied consent to construct the pipeline on the company's preferred route through culturally and ecologically sensitive lands in their unceded territory, leading to [[2020 Canadian pipeline and railway protests|nationwide protests]].<ref>http://unistoten.camp/no-pipelines/background-of-the-campaign/</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=No Surrender |first1=Alleen |last1=Brown |first2=Amber |last2=Bracken |website=The Intercept |publisher=First Look Media |url=https://theintercept.com/2020/02/23/wetsuweten-protest-coastal-gaslink-pipeline/ |accessdate=February 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''Prince Rupert Gas Transmission project''' \u2013 In January 2013 it was announced that TransCanada was selected by [[Petronas]] to design, build, own, and operate<ref name=TCnews>{{cite news|title=TransCanada Selected to Develop $6 Billion in Natural Gas Infrastructure to Prince Rupert, British Columbia|url=http://www.transcanada.com/6187.html|accessdate=June 12, 2013|newspaper=TransCanada|date=January 9, 2013|format=news release}}</ref> the Prince Rupert Gas Transmission project, a gas pipeline that would transport natural gas from the Montney region near [[Fort St. John, British Columbia]] to a LNG terminal planned by Progress Energy Canada Ltd. in [[Port Edward, British Columbia]] on [[Lelu Island (British Columbia)|Lelu Island]] near [[Prince Rupert, British Columbia]].<ref name=AOM01913>{{cite news|title=B.C. LNG exports take a step forward with TransCanada announcement: TCPL to build $5.1 billion pipeline that will feed coastal terminal|url=http://www.albertaoilmagazine.com/2013/01/b-c-lng-exports-take-a-step-forward-with-transcanada-announcement/|accessdate=June 12, 2013|newspaper=Alberta Oil Magazine|date=January 9, 2013|author=Darren Campbell}}</ref> The project faced opposition from the [[Gitxsan]] first nation due to concerns about the impact it would have on salmon in the [[Skeena River]]. On July 25, 2017, Petronas announced they were abandoning the [[Lelu Island (British Columbia)#Proposed Pacific NorthWest LNG export facility|Pacific NorthWest LNG]] proposal and TransCanada said they were \"reviewing our options related to our proposed Prince Rupert Gas Transmission (PRGT) project\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.transcanada.com/en/operations/natural-gas/prince-rupert-gas-transmission-project/|title=TransCanada Prince Rupert Gas Transmission Project \u2013 Overview|website=www.transcanada.com|language=en|access-date=2018-03-17}}</ref>\n\n===Liquids pipelines===\nTC Energy's Liquids pipelines connect Alberta crude oil supplies to U.S. refining markets.<ref name=\"2018 Annual Report\"/>\n\n*'''[[Keystone Pipeline System]] (4,324&nbsp;km)''' The pipeline system transports crude oil from [[Hardisty, Alberta]], to U.S. markets at [[Wood River (Illinois)|Wood River]] and [[Patoka, Illinois]], [[Cushing, Oklahoma]], and the U.S. Gulf Coast. The Keystone System transports approximately 20% of Western Canadian crude oil to export markets.\n*'''[[Keystone XL]] (1,906&nbsp;km)''' The proposed pipeline will transport crude oil from Hardisty, Alberta to Steele City, Nebraska, to expand capacity of the Keystone Pipeline System. In 2017, President [[Donald Trump]] granted a U.S. Presidential Permit, TransCanada received approval for a Nebraska pipeline route and secured sufficient commercial support to commence construction preparation for the Keystone XL project. The company expects to begin construction in 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/keystone-xl-transcanada-pipeline-calgary-support-contracts-oil-alberta-1.4492795|title=Keystone XL pipeline has strong commercial support, TransCanada says|work=CBC News|access-date=2018-03-13|language=en}}</ref>\n*'''Grand Rapids (460&nbsp;km)''' Transports crude oil from the producing area northwest of Fort McMurray, Alberta, to the Edmonton/Heartland, Alberta market region. In October 2012, TransCanada formed a 50\u201350 CAD$3bn joint-venture with Phoenix Energy Holdings Ltd. (the Canadian subsidiary of [[PetroChina]]) to develop the 500&nbsp;km Grand Rapids Pipeline.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/finance/stocks/TRP/key-developments/article/2631892|title=${Instrument_CompanyName} ${Instrument_Ric}  Key Developments|author=Reuters staff|website=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=6 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Energy===\n[[File:Bruce-Nuclear-Szmurlo.jpg|right|thumb|[[Bruce Nuclear Generating Station]]]]\nTC Energy's Energy division consists of power generation and unregulated natural gas storage assets. The power business consists of approximately 7,000 megawatts (MW) of generation capacity owned or under development. These assets are located primarily in Canada and are powered by natural gas, nuclear, and wind.<ref name=\"2018 Annual Report\"/>\n*'''Western Power''' These assets include approximately 1,000 MW of power generation capacity through four natural gas-fired cogeneration facilities in Alberta and one in Arizona.\n*'''Eastern Power''' These assets include approximately 2,900 MW of power generation capacity in Eastern Canada.\n*'''[[Bruce Power]]''' This operates the [[Bruce Nuclear Generating Station]] in Ontario. Comprising eight nuclear units with a combined capacity of approximately 6,400 MW, it is currently the largest operating nuclear power plant in the world. TC Energy holds a 48.4% interest in the asset.\n\n==Ownership==\nAs of February 2020, the bulk of the share capital of TC Energy is owned by 488 [[institutional investors]], who compose 62% of the stock. The dominant shareholder is the [[Royal Bank of Canada]], which owns a fraction over 8% of the company. The [[Big Five (banks)]] together own more than 17% of the outstanding share capital. Significant holdings accrue to the [[Caisse de d\u00e9p\u00f4t et placement du Qu\u00e9bec]] and the [[OMERS]].<ref name=\"nasdaq\">{{cite web |title=TRP TC Energy Corporation Common Stock |url=https://www.nasdaq.com/market-activity/stocks/trp/institutional-holdings |publisher=Nasdaq, Inc.}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\n===Keystone XL Pipeline===\n{{Main|Keystone XL Pipeline}}\n\nTC Energy first proposed the Keystone XL pipeline in 2008.<ref name=downstream4>{{cite news | url = http://www.downstreamtoday.com/news/article.aspx?a_id=11336 | title = TransCanada Proposes Second Oil Pipeline | newspaper = Lincoln Journal-Star | publisher = Downstream Today | first = Art | last = Hovey | date = 2008-06-12 | accessdate = 2008-07-18}}</ref> The proposal faced widespread grassroots opposition with tactics including tree sits in the path of the pipeline<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/business/article/Protesters-in-Texas-climb-trees-to-block-pipeline-3891002.php |title=Protesters in Texas climb trees to block pipeline work |publisher=Houston Chronicle |date=September 25, 2012}}</ref> and civil disobedience by celebrities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.suntimes.com/news/nation/15598994-418/daryl-hannah-freed-following-arrest-in-pipeline-protest.html |title=Daryl Hannah freed following arrest in pipeline protest |publisher=Chicago Sun-Times |date=Oct 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe Keystone XL Pipeline would transport 830,000 barrels of oil per day from the [[Athabasca oil sands]] to [[Steele City, Nebraska]], upon completion. Critics{{who|date=October 2018}} state that by developing the oil sands, fossil fuels will be readily available and the trend toward warming of the atmosphere won't be curbed.{{citation needed|date=October 2018}} The fate of the pipeline is therefore held up as symbolic of America's energy future.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-30103078|title=Why is the Keystone XL pipeline so disputed?|date=2017|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-03-15|language=en-GB}}</ref> Critics{{who|date=October 2018}} have raised concerns about the risks of spillage, as the [[Sandhills (Nebraska)|Sandhills]] region of Nebraska is a fragile ecosystem.{{citation needed|date=October 2018}}\n\nAfter four years of organizing by those opposed to the Keystone XL, the administration of U.S. President Obama rejected the pipeline on November 3, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kerry|first1=John|title=Department of State: Record of Decision and National Interest Determination|url=http://keystonepipeline-xl.state.gov/documents/organization/249450.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151121145230/http://keystonepipeline-xl.state.gov/documents/organization/249450.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=21 November 2015|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Whitehouse|first1=Obama|title=Obama rejects TransCanada's Keystone XL pipeline|url=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/the-press-office/2015/11/06/statement-president-keystone-xl-pipeline|accessdate=6 November 2015|publisher=Whitehouse|date=6 November 2015}}</ref> Early in his tenure in 2017, President [[Donald Trump]] signed presidential memoranda to revive both Keystone XL and [[Dakota Access Pipeline|Dakota Access]] pipelines. The order would expedite the environmental review that Trump described as an \"incredibly cumbersome, long, horrible permitting process\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Mufson |first=Steven |date=January 24, 2017 |title=Trump seeks to revive Dakota Access, Keystone XL oil pipelines |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2017/01/24/trump-gives-green-light-to-dakota-access-keystone-xl-oil-pipelines/ |newspaper=[[Washington Post]] |location=Washington, DC |access-date=January 24, 2017}}</ref> Subsequently, Donald Trump signed a presidential permit to allow TransCanada to build the Keystone XL pipeline on March 24, 2017.<ref name=\"guardian-24mar2017\">{{cite news|last1=Jamieson|first1=Amber|last2=Vaughan|first2=Adam|title=Keystone XL: Trump issues permit to begin construction of pipeline|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/mar/24/keystone-xl-pipeline-permit-trump-administration|accessdate=March 24, 2017|newspaper=The Guardian|date=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThis action by Trump inspired another wave of protests and rallies against the pipeline.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://calgaryherald.com/business/energy/keystone-xl-hundreds-protest-at-white-house-signalling-upcoming-pipeline-fight|title=Keystone XL: Hundreds protest at White House, signalling upcoming pipeline fight|date=2017-01-25|work=Calgary Herald|access-date=2018-03-15|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===Use of eminent domain===\nIn October 2011, TransCanada was involved in up to 56 separate [[eminent domain]] actions against landowners in Texas and South Dakota who refused to give permission to the company to build the [[Keystone Pipeline]] through their land.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/10/18/us/transcanada-in-eminent-domain-fight-over-pipeline.html |title=Eminent Domain Fight Has a Canadian Twist |publisher=New York Times |date=Oct 17, 2011}}</ref> However, on August 23, 2012, Texas Judge Bill Harris ruled that TransCanada had the right of eminent domain and could lease or purchase land from owners who refused to sign an agreement with the company for a public [[right of way]] for the pipeline.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}} The landowners had said that the pipeline was not open to other companies, and so did not meet the criteria for eminent domain.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/texas-judge-rules-in-favor-of-transcanada-in-eminent-domain-case/2012/08/23/87744776-ecda-11e1-a80b-9f898562d010_story.html |title=Keystone pipeline clears a hurdle |publisher=Washington Post |date=Aug 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\nFor several years in 2014-2017 as TransCanada was acquiring Columbia Gas Transmission, dozens of private properties were occupied by their natural gas MB Line construction in Baltimore and Harford County Maryland using hired armed State of Maryland Transit Police and Baltimore City policeman.  .\n\n==Spills==\n\nThe [[Keystone Pipeline]] has had three significant leaks since it opened in 2010. It has leaked approximately 400 barrels in North Dakota in 2011 and South Dakota in 2016, and approximately 5000 barrels in South Dakota in 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-pipeline-keystone-spills/keystones-existing-pipeline-spills-far-more-than-predicted-to-regulators-idUSKBN1DR1CS|title=Keystone's existing pipeline spills far more than predicted to...|date= 2017-11-27|work=Reuters|accessdate=2018-03-15}}</ref>\n\n===Marshall County, South Dakota leak 2017===\n\nOn November 16, 2017, [[oil leak]]ed from the pipeline in [[Marshall County, South Dakota]], for 15 minutes before the flow of oil could be stopped. The company reported the amount as over 210,000 gallons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ksfy.com/content/news/Crews-cleaning-up-Keystone-Pipeline-leak-in-Marshall-County-458046943.html|title=Crews cleaning up Keystone Pipeline leak in Marshall County|publisher=KSFY ABC|date=November 16, 2017|accessdate=November 16, 2017}}</ref> TransCanada reported it discovered the leak in [[Amherst, South Dakota]], at 6 am on Thursday after systems detected a drop in pressure in the northern leg of the pipeline.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-transcanada-keystone-spill/transcanadas-keystone-pipeline-shut-after-5000-barrel-leak-in-u-s-idUSKBN1DG30K|title=TransCanada's Keystone pipeline shut after 5,000-barrel leak in U.S.|publisher=Reuters|date=November 16, 2017|accessdate=November 16, 2017}}</ref> The leak was discovered about 35 miles south of the Ludden pump station.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://heavy.com/news/2017/11/keystone-pipeline-leak-oil-spill-photos/|title=Keystone Pipeline Leak: More Than 200,000 Gallons of Oil Spilled|publisher=Heavy.com|date=November 16, 2017|accessdate=November 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, a federal investigation showed that the spill was almost twice as large as TransCanada had claimed in November, and that it was the seventh-largest onshore oil spill since 2002. The study showed that 407,000 gallons, not 210,000 gallons, had spilled.<ref name=\"VICE\">[https://news.vice.com/en_us/article/evqqmk/egypts-jon-stewart-watched-the-egyptian-elections-from-la \"The Keystone Pipeline oil spill was nearly twice as big as TransCanada said\"], ''[[Vice News]]'', Sarah Sax, April 10, 2018</ref> Also in April 2018, ''[[Reuters]]'' reviewed documents that showed that Keystone had \"leaked substantially more oil, and more often, in the United States than the company indicated to regulators in risk assessments before operations began in 2010\".<ref name=\"DOUBLE\">[https://mobile.reuters.com/article/amp/idUSKBN1HE0T7 \"Keystone pipeline leak in South Dakota about double previous estimate: paper\"], Reuters, April 7, 2018</ref>\n\n==Operational projects==\n===Operational natural gas pipelines===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n! width=\"15%\" | Name\n! width=\"5%\" |Country\n! width=\"10%\" |Length\n! width=\"2.5%\" |TransCanada's participation\n! width=\"47.5%\" |Description\n|-\n||NGTL System\n|Canada\n| align=\"right\" |{{convert|24,320|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}\n| align=\"right\" | 100\n|| Receives, transports and delivers natural gas within Alberta and B.C., and connects with the Canadian Mainline, Foothills system and third-party pipelines.\n|-\n||Canadian Mainline\n|Canada\n| align=\"right\" |{{convert|14,077|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}\n| align=\"right\" | 100 \n||Transports natural gas from the Alberta/Saskatchewanborder and the Ontario/U.S. border to serve easternCanada and interconnects to the U.S.\n\n|-\n||Foothills\n|Canada\n| align=\"right\" |{{convert|1,241|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}\n| align=\"right\" | 100 \n||Transports natural gas from central Alberta to the U.S. border for export to the U.S. Midwest, PacificNorthwest, California and Nevada\n|-\n||Trans Qu\u00e9bec & Maritimes\n|Canada\n| align=\"right\" |{{convert|572|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}\n| align=\"right\" |50\n||Connects with the Canadian Mainline near the Ontario/Qu\u00e9bec border to transport natural gas to the Montr\u00e9al to Qu\u00e9bec City corridor, and interconnects with the Portland pipeline system that serves the northeast U.S.\n|-\n||Ventures LP\n|Canada\n| align=\"right\" |{{convert|161|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}\n| align=\"right\" |100\n||Transports natural gas to the oil sands region near Fort McMurray, Alberta. It also includes a 27&nbsp;km (17 mile) pipeline supplying natural gas to a petrochemical complex at Joffre, Alberta.\n|-\n||Great Lakes Canada\n|Canada\n| align=\"right\" |{{convert|58|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}\n| align=\"right\" |100\n|| Transports natural gas from the Great Lakes system in the U.S. to Ontario, near Dawn, through a connection at the U.S. border underneath the St. Clair River\n|-\n||ANR\n|United States\n| align=\"right\" |{{convert|15,109|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}\n| align=\"right\" |100\n||Transports natural gas from various supply basins to markets throughout the Midwest and Gulf Coast.\n|-\n||Bison\n|United States\n| align=\"right\" |{{convert|488|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}\n| align=\"right\" | 25.7\n||Transports natural gas from the Powder River Basin in Wyoming to Northern Border in North Dakota.\n|-\n||Columbia Gas\n|United States\n| align=\"right\" |{{convert|18,113|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}\n| align=\"right\" | 100 \n||Transports natural gas from supply primarily in the Appalachian Basin to markets throughout the U.S. Northeast.\n|-\n||Columbia Gulf\n|United States\n| align=\"right\" |{{convert|5,377|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}\n| align=\"right\" |100\n||Transports natural gas to various markets and pipeline interconnects in the southern U.S. and Gulf Coast.\n|-\n||Crossroads\n|United States\n| align=\"right\" |{{convert|325|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}\n| align=\"right\" | 100 \n||Interstate natural gas pipeline operating in Indiana and Ohio with multiple interconnects to other pipelines.\n|-\n||Gas Transmission Northwest\n|United States\n| align=\"right\" |{{convert|2,216|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}\n| align=\"right\" | 25.7\n||Transports WCSB and Rockies natural gas to Washington, Oregon and California. Connects with Tuscarora and Foothills.\n|-\n||Great Lakes\n|United States\n| align=\"right\" |{{convert|3,404|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}\n| align=\"right\" | 65.5\n||Connects with the Canadian Mainline near Emerson, Manitoba, and to Great Lakes Canada near St Clair, Ontario, plus interconnects with ANR at Crystal Falls and Farwell in Michigan, to transport natural gas to eastern Canada and the U.S. Upper Midwest\n|-\n||Iroquois\n|United States\n| align=\"right\" |{{convert|669|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}\n| align=\"right\" | 13.4\n||Connects with the Canadian Mainline and serves markets in New York.\n|-\n||Millennium\n|United States\n| align=\"right\" |{{convert|407|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}\n| align=\"right\" | 47.5\n||Natural gas pipeline supplied by local production, storage fields and interconnecting upstream pipelines to serve markets along its route and to the U.S. Northeast.\n|-\n||North Baja\n|United States\n| align=\"right\" |{{convert|138|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}\n| align=\"right\" | 25.7\n||Transports natural gas between Arizona and California, and connects with a third-party pipeline on the California/ Mexico border. \n|-\n||Northern Border\n|United States\n| align=\"right\" |{{convert|2,272|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}\n| align=\"right\" | 12.9\n||Transports WCSB, Bakken and Rockies natural gas from connections with Foothills and Bison to U.S. Midwest markets. \n|-\n||Portland\n|United States\n| align=\"right\" |{{convert|475|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}\n| align=\"right\" | 15.9\n||Connects with TQM near East Hereford, Qu\u00e9bec to deliver natural gas to customers in the U.S. Northeast. \n|-\n||Tuscarora\n|United States\n| align=\"right\" |{{convert|491|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}\n| align=\"right\" | 25.7\n||Transports natural gas from GTN at Malin, Oregon to markets in northeastern California and northwestern Nevada.\n|-\n||Guadalajara\n|Mexico\n| align=\"right\" |{{convert|315|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}\n| align=\"right\" | 100\n||Transports natural gas from Manzanillo, Colima to Guadalajara, Jalisco.\n|-\n||Mazatl\u00e1n\n|Mexico\n| align=\"right\" |{{convert|491|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}\n| align=\"right\" | 100\n||Transports natural gas from El Oro to Mazatl\u00e1n, Sinaloa inMexico. Connects to the Topolobampo Pipeline at El Oro\n|-\n||Tamazunchale\n|Mexico\n| align=\"right\" |{{convert|375|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}\n| align=\"right\" | 100\n||Transports natural gas from Naranjos, Veracruz in east central Mexico to Tamazunchale, San Luis Potos\u00ed and on to El Sauz, Quer\u00e9taro.\n|-\n||Topolobampo\n|Mexico\n| align=\"right\" |{{convert|560|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}\n| align=\"right\" | 100\n||Transports natural gas to Topolobampo, Sinaloa, from interconnects with third-party pipelines in El Oro, Sinaloa and El Encino, Chihuahua in Mexico \n|}\n\n===Operational liquids pipelines===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n! width=\"15%\" | Name\n! width=\"5%\" |Country\n! width=\"10%\" |Length\n! width=\"2.5%\" |TransCanada's participation\n! width=\"47.5%\" |Description\n|-\n||Keystone Pipeline System\n|Canada\n| align=\"right\" |{{convert|4,324|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}\n| align=\"right\" | 100\n||Transports crude oil from Hardisty, Alberta, to U.S. markets at Wood River and Patoka, Illinois, Cushing, Oklahoma, and the U.S. Gulf Coast. \n|-\n||Marketlink\n|Canada\n| align=\"right\" |\n| align=\"right\" | 100 \n||Terminal and pipeline facilities to transport crude oil from the market hub at Cushing, Oklahoma to the U.S. Gulf Coast refining markets on facilities that form part of the Keystone Pipeline System.\n\n|-\n||Grand Rapids\n|Canada\n| align=\"right\" |{{convert|460|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}\n| align=\"right\" |50\n||Transports crude oil from the producing area northwest of Fort McMurray, Alberta, to the Edmonton/Heartland, Alberta, market region\n|-\n||Northern Courier\n|Canada\n| align=\"right\" |{{convert|90|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}\n| align=\"right\" |100\n||Transports bitumen and diluent between the Fort Hills mine site and Suncor Energy's terminal located north of Fort McMurray, Alberta.\n|}\n\n===Operational power projects===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n! width=\"30%\" | Name\n! width=\"10%\" | Fuel Type\n! width=\"10%\" | Net Installed Capacity ([[Megawatt|MW]])\n! width=\"5%\" | TransCanada's participation\n! width=\"50%\" | Description\n|-\n||Bear Creek\n|Natural Gas\n| align=\"right\" |100\n| align=\"right\" | 100\n||Cogeneration plant in Grande Prairie, Alberta. \n|-\n||Carseland\n|Natural Gas\n| align=\"right\" |95\n| align=\"right\" | 100 \n||Cogeneration plant in Carseland, Alberta.\n|-\n||Mackay River\n|Natural Gas\n| align=\"right\" |205\n| align=\"right\" |100\n||Cogeneration plant in Fort McMurray, Alberta. \n|-\n||Redwater\n|Natural Gas\n| align=\"right\" |46\n| align=\"right\" |100\n||Cogeneration plant in Redwater, Alberta. \n|-\n||B\u00e9cancour\n|Natural Gas\n| align=\"right\" |550\n| align=\"right\" |100\n||Cogeneration plant in Trois-Rivi\u00e8res, Qu\u00e9bec. \n|-\n||Grandview\n|Natural Gas\n| align=\"right\" |90\n| align=\"right\" | 100 \n||Cogeneration plant in Saint John, New Brunswick. \n|-\n||Halton Hills\n|Natural Gas\n| align=\"right\" |683\n| align=\"right\" | 100 \n||Combined-cycle plant in Halton Hills, Ontario.\n|-\n||[[Portlands Energy Centre|Portlands]]\n|Natural Gas\n| align=\"right\" |275\n| align=\"right\" |50\n||Joint venture with [[Ontario Power Generation]]. Combined-cycle plant in Toronto, Ontario. \n|-\n||[[Bruce Nuclear Generating Station|Bruce]]\n|Nuclear\n| align=\"right\" |3099\n| align=\"right\" |48.4\n||As part of [[Bruce Power|Bruce Power Limited Partnership]]. Eight operating reactors in Tiverton, Ontario. Bruce Power leases the eight nuclear facilities from OPG. \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Companies}}\n*{{Official|https://www.tcenergy.com/}}\n*[http://www.keystone-xl.com/ Keystone XL Pipeline website]\n\n{{S&P/TSX 60}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Transcanada Corp.}}\n[[Category:TC Energy| ]]\n[[Category:Crude oil pipelines companies]]\n[[Category:Energy companies of Canada]]\n[[Category:Natural gas companies of Canada]]\n[[Category:Natural gas pipeline companies]]\n[[Category:Electric power companies of Canada]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Calgary]]\n[[Category:Holding companies of Canada]]\n[[Category:Energy companies established in 1951]]\n[[Category:Non-renewable resource companies established in 1951]]\n[[Category:1951 establishments in Canada]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Toronto Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:S&P/TSX 60 Index]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian energy company}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = TC Energy Corporation\n| logo = TC Energy Logo May 2019.svg\n| image = TransCanapr20.JPG\n| image_size = 150px\n| image_caption = [[TransCanada Tower]], the company's head office in Calgary\n| type = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as = {{Plainlist|\n* {{TSX|TRP}}\n* [[S&P/TSX 60|S&P/TSX 60 component]]}}\n| industry = [[Energy industry|Energy]]\n| founder = \n| defunct = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| hq_location = [[TransCanada Tower]]\n| hq_location_city = [[Calgary]], [[Alberta]]\n| hq_location_country = Canada\n| area_served = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Canada]]\n* [[Mexico]]\n* [[United States]]}}\n| key_people = [[Russ Girling]], President and CEO\n| production = \n| services = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Pipeline transport]]\n* [[Natural gas storage]]\n* [[Electricity generation]]}} \n| revenue = {{increase}} [[C$]]13.68 billion (2018)<ref name=\"2018 Annual Report\">{{cite report |url=https://www.tcenergy.com/globalassets/pdfs/investors/tc-annual-report.pdf |date=2019 |title=Annual Report 2018 |access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n| net_income = {{increase}} [[C$]]3.54 billion (2018)<ref name=\"2018 Annual Report\"/>\n| assets = {{increase}} [[C$]]98.92 billion (2018)<ref name=\"2018 Annual Report\"/>\n| equity = {{increase}} [[C$]]25.36 billion (2018)<ref name=\"2018 Annual Report\"/>\n| num_employees = 7,000<ref name= \"Energy and Commitment\">{{cite |url=https://www.tcenergy.com/globalassets/pdfs/media/fact-sheets/tc-our-business-at-a-glance.pdf |work=TC Energy |title=Fact sheet}}</ref>\n| foundation = 1951\n| locations = <!-- Number of locations, stores, offices, etc. -->\n| homepage = {{URL|https://www.tcenergy.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''TC Energy Corporation''' (formerly '''TransCanada Corporation''') is a major North American [[energy company]], based in [[Calgary]], [[Alberta]], Canada, that develops and operates energy infrastructure in Canada, the United States, and Mexico. The company operates three core businesses: Natural Gas Pipelines, Liquids Pipelines and Energy.\n\nThe Natural Gas Pipeline network includes {{convert|92,600|km|mi|0|abbr=off}} of [[gas pipeline]], which transports more than 25% of North American natural gas demand. The Liquids Pipelines division includes {{convert|4,900|km|mi|0|abbr=off}} of oil pipeline, which ships 590,000 barrels of crude oil per day, which is about 20% of Western Canadian exports. The Energy division owns or has interests in 11 power generation facilities with combined capacity of 6,600 megawatts (MW). These power sources include nuclear and natural gas fired.<ref name=\"2018 Annual Report\"/>\n\nThe company was founded in 1951 in Calgary.<ref>{{cite book |first=William |last=Kilbourn|authorlink=William Kilbourn |year=1970 |title=Pipeline: TransCanada and the Great Debate |url=https://archive.org/details/pipelinetranscan00kilb |url-access=registration | page= [https://archive.org/details/pipelinetranscan00kilb/page/29 29]}}</ref> TC Energy is the largest [[shareholder]] in, and owns the [[general partner]] of, [[TC PipeLines]].\n\n==History==\nThe company was incorporated in 1951 by a Special Act of Parliament as Trans-Canada Pipe Lines Limited.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fundinguniverse.com/company-histories/transcanada-pipelines-limited-history/|title=History of TRANSCANADA PIPELINES LIMITED \u2013 FundingUniverse|website=www.fundinguniverse.com|language=en|access-date=2018-03-13}}</ref> The purpose of the company was to develop the [[TransCanada pipeline]] (now known as the Canadian Mainline) to supply eastern Canadian markets with natural gas produced in the west.\n\nIn 1998, TransCanada Pipelines merged with [[NOVA Chemicals|NOVA Corporation]]'s pipeline business, keeping the TransCanada name and becoming \"the fourth largest energy services company in North America\".<ref name=\"Merger\">{{Cite web |title=TransCanada, Nova Complete Merger |url=https://www.naturalgasintel.com/articles/92796-transcanada-nova-complete-merger |publisher=Natural Gas Intellicence |date=1998-07-06 |accessdate=2020-03-01}}</ref>\n\n[[File:TransCanada Logo.svg|thumb|Logo of TransCanada before rebranding as TC Energy in 2019|alt=]]\n\nSeeking to expand its presence in the United States, in 2016, TransCanada acquired Columbia Pipeline Group for US$13 billion. The Columbia acquisition added a pipeline network in Pennsylvania and surrounding states, where the [[Marcellus Formation|Marcellus]] and [[Utica Shale|Utica]] shale gas formations are located.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://business.financialpost.com/commodities/energy/transcanada-corp-to-acquire-columbia-pipeline-group-in-us13-billion-deal|title=TransCanada Corp to overhaul its business in US$13B acquisition of Columbia Pipeline Group|date=2016-03-18|work=Financial Post|access-date=2018-03-15|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, the company changed its name from TransCanada Corporation to TC Energy Corporation to better reflect the company's business, which includes pipelines, power generation and energy storage operations in Canada, the United States and Mexico.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-transcanada-results-idUSKCN1S911H|title=Pipeline company TransCanada changes name to TC Energy|last=Williams|first=Nia|date=2019-05-03|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-05-05|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://o.canada.com/commodities/not-a-brand-change-new-name-same-pipeline-challenges-for-tc-energy/wcm/65c5dc2d-2f5b-4664-be29-64b476d129de|title=\u2018Not a brand change\u2019: New name, same pipeline challenges for TC Energy|date=2019-05-03|website=canada.com|language=en-ca|access-date=2019-05-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.commondreams.org/news/2019/05/04/transcanada-can-change-its-name-say-opponents-keystone-xl-will-never-see-light-day|title=TransCanada Can Change Its Name, Say Opponents, But Keystone XL Will Never See 'The Light of Day'|last=Queally|first=Jon|date=2019-05-04|website=Common Dreams|language=en|access-date=2019-05-05}}</ref>\n\n==Operations==\n===Natural gas pipelines===\nTC Energy's natural gas pipelines business builds, owns and operates a network of natural gas pipelines across North America that connects gas production to interconnects and end use markets. The company transports over 25% of continental daily natural gas demand through 91,900&nbsp;km (57,100&nbsp;mi) of pipelines. In addition, the company owns 535 Bcf of natural gas storage facilities, making TC Energy one of the largest natural gas storage providers in North America. This segment is TC Energy's largest segment, generating approximately two-thirds of the company's [[EBITDA]] in 2017. The Natural Gas Pipelines business is split into three operating segments: Canadian Natural Gas Pipelines, U.S. Natural Gas Pipelines, and Mexico Natural Gas Pipelines.<ref name=\"2018 Annual Report\"/>\n\nThe major pipeline systems include:\n\n*'''NGTL System (24,320&nbsp;km)''' A wholly-owned subsidiary, NOVA Gas Transmission Ltd., connects gas producers in the [[Western Canadian Sedimentary Basin]] with consumers and exports.<ref>{{Cite web |title=NGTL System |url=https://www.tcenergy.com/operations/natural-gas/ngtl-system/ |publisher=TC Energy |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309000228/https://www.tcenergy.com/operations/natural-gas/ngtl-system/ |archivedate=2020-03-09|accessdate=2020-03-09}}</ref> TC Energy has the largest and most extensive natural gas network in Alberta.<ref name=pri>{{cite news|title=TransCanada rule change raises ire of producers|agency=Financial Post|last=Morgan|first=Geoffrey|newspaper=Saskatchewan StarPhoenix|url=https://www.pressreader.com/canada/saskatoon-starphoenix/20171101/282226600986366|date=November 1, 2017}}</ref>\n*'''[[TransCanada pipeline|Canadian Mainline]] (14,077&nbsp;km)''' this pipeline serves as a long haul delivery system transporting natural gas from the [[Western Canadian Sedimentary Basin]] across Canada to Ontario and Qu\u00e9bec to deliver gas to downstream Canadian and U.S. markets. The pipeline has evolved accommodate additional supply connections closer to its markets. The mainline is over 60 years old <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.transcanada.com/en/operations/natural-gas/canadian-mainline/|title=TransCanada Canadian Mainline \u2013 Overview|author=|date=|website=www.transcanada.com}}</ref>\n*'''[[Columbia Gas Transmission|Columbia Gas]] (18,113&nbsp;km)''' This natural gas transportation system serves the [[Appalachian Basin]], which contains the [[Marcellus Formation|Marcellus]] and [[Utica Shale|Utica]] plays, two of the largest natural gas shale plays in North America. The system also interconnects with other pipelines that provide access to the U.S. Northeast and the Gulf of Mexico.'''\n*'''[[ANR Pipeline|ANR Pipeline System]] (15,109&nbsp;km)''' This pipeline system connects supply basins and markets throughout the U.S. Midwest, and south to the Gulf of Mexico. This includes connecting supply in Texas, Oklahoma, the Appalachian Basin and the Gulf of Mexico to markets in Wisconsin, Michigan, Illinois and Ohio. In addition, ANR has bi-directional capability on its Southeast Mainline and delivers gas produced from the Appalachian basin to customers throughout the Gulf Coast Region.\n*'''[[Columbia Gulf Transmission|Columbia Gulf]] (5,377&nbsp;km)''' \u2013 This pipeline system was originally designed as a long haul delivery system transporting supply from the Gulf of Mexico to major demand markets in the U.S. Northeast. The pipeline is now transitioning to a north-to-south flow and expanding to accommodate new supply in the Appalachian Basin and its interconnects with Columbia Gas and other pipelines to deliver gas to various Gulf Coast markets.\n*'''Mexico Pipeline Network (1,680&nbsp;km)''' \u2013 This consists of a growing network of natural gas pipelines in Mexico.\n\nProjects in development include:\n\n'''[[Coastal GasLink Pipeline|Coastal GasLink Pipeline Project]]''' \u2013 In June 2012 it was announced that TransCanada was selected by Shell and [[LNG Canada]] partners [[Korea Gas Corporation]], [[Mitsubishi]] Corporation and [[PetroChina]] Company Limited (to which [[Petronas]] of Malaysia was added in 2018) to design, build, own and operate<ref name=TC6512>{{cite news|title=TransCanada Selected by Shell and Partners to Develop Multi-Billion Dollar Natural Gas Pipeline to Canada's West Coast|url=http://www.transcanada.com/6054.html|accessdate=June 12, 2013|newspaper=TransCanada|date=June 5, 2012|format=news release}}</ref> the Coastal GasLink pipeline between northeastern B.C. gas fields near [[Dawson Creek, British Columbia]], and the [[LNG Canada]] LNG liquefaction, storage and export facility in the port of [[Kitimat]], on the [[Douglas Channel]].<ref name=Tyee01913>{{cite news|title=TransCanada to build $5-billion shale gas pipeline project near Prince Rupert|url=https://thetyee.ca/Blogs/TheHook/2013/01/09/TransCanada-Shale-Project/|accessdate=June 12, 2013|newspaper=The Tyee|date=January 9, 2013|last=Krugel|first=Lauren|format=blog}}</ref><ref name=HomeCoastal>{{cite web|title=Home page|url=http://www.coastalgaslink.com/|publisher=Coastal GasLink Pipeline Ltd., a wholly owned subsidiary of TransCanada PipeLines Limited|accessdate=June 12, 2013|quote=Coastal GasLink Pipeline Ltd., a wholly owned subsidiary of TransCanada PipeLines Limited, proposes to develop a natural gas pipeline from northeast B.C. to the west coast of B.C. to serve export markets.}}</ref><ref name = ProjectDescription >[http://www.coastalgaslink.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/Coastal-GasLink-Project-Description-Nov-07_12.pdf Coastal GasLink Pipeline project description]</ref><ref name=GM6512>{{cite news|title=TransCanada wins $4-billion pipeline contract|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/industry-news/energy-and-resources/transcanada-wins-4-billion-pipeline-contract/article4231488/|accessdate=June 12, 2013|newspaper=The Globe and Mail|date=June 5, 2012|author=Nathan VanderKlippe}}</ref>\nThe investment and construction decisions for the [[LNG Canada]] and Coastal GasLink Pipeline Project were officially confirmed early October 2018, for completion by 2024-2025. However, hereditary chiefs of the [[Wet\u02bcsuwet\u02bcen]] have denied consent to construct the pipeline on the company's preferred route through culturally and ecologically sensitive lands in their unceded territory, leading to [[2020 Canadian pipeline and railway protests|nationwide protests]].<ref>http://unistoten.camp/no-pipelines/background-of-the-campaign/</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=No Surrender |first1=Alleen |last1=Brown |first2=Amber |last2=Bracken |website=The Intercept |publisher=First Look Media |url=https://theintercept.com/2020/02/23/wetsuweten-protest-coastal-gaslink-pipeline/ |accessdate=February 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''Prince Rupert Gas Transmission project''' \u2013 In January 2013 it was announced that TransCanada was selected by [[Petronas]] to design, build, own, and operate<ref name=TCnews>{{cite news|title=TransCanada Selected to Develop $6 Billion in Natural Gas Infrastructure to Prince Rupert, British Columbia|url=http://www.transcanada.com/6187.html|accessdate=June 12, 2013|newspaper=TransCanada|date=January 9, 2013|format=news release}}</ref> the Prince Rupert Gas Transmission project, a gas pipeline that would transport natural gas from the Montney region near [[Fort St. John, British Columbia]] to a LNG terminal planned by Progress Energy Canada Ltd. in [[Port Edward, British Columbia]] on [[Lelu Island (British Columbia)|Lelu Island]] near [[Prince Rupert, British Columbia]].<ref name=AOM01913>{{cite news|title=B.C. LNG exports take a step forward with TransCanada announcement: TCPL to build $5.1 billion pipeline that will feed coastal terminal|url=http://www.albertaoilmagazine.com/2013/01/b-c-lng-exports-take-a-step-forward-with-transcanada-announcement/|accessdate=June 12, 2013|newspaper=Alberta Oil Magazine|date=January 9, 2013|author=Darren Campbell}}</ref> The project faced opposition from the [[Gitxsan]] first nation due to concerns about the impact it would have on salmon in the [[Skeena River]]. On July 25, 2017, Petronas announced they were abandoning the [[Lelu Island (British Columbia)#Proposed Pacific NorthWest LNG export facility|Pacific NorthWest LNG]] proposal and TransCanada said they were \"reviewing our options related to our proposed Prince Rupert Gas Transmission (PRGT) project\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.transcanada.com/en/operations/natural-gas/prince-rupert-gas-transmission-project/|title=TransCanada Prince Rupert Gas Transmission Project \u2013 Overview|website=www.transcanada.com|language=en|access-date=2018-03-17}}</ref>\n\n===Liquids pipelines===\nTC Energy's Liquids pipelines connect Alberta crude oil supplies to U.S. refining markets.<ref name=\"2018 Annual Report\"/>\n\n*'''[[Keystone Pipeline System]] (4,324&nbsp;km)''' The pipeline system transports crude oil from [[Hardisty, Alberta]], to U.S. markets at [[Wood River (Illinois)|Wood River]] and [[Patoka, Illinois]], [[Cushing, Oklahoma]], and the U.S. Gulf Coast. The Keystone System transports approximately 20% of Western Canadian crude oil to export markets.\n*'''[[Keystone XL]] (1,906&nbsp;km)''' The proposed pipeline will transport crude oil from Hardisty, Alberta to Steele City, Nebraska, to expand capacity of the Keystone Pipeline System. In 2017, President [[Donald Trump]] granted a U.S. Presidential Permit, TransCanada received approval for a Nebraska pipeline route and secured sufficient commercial support to commence construction preparation for the Keystone XL project. The company expects to begin construction in 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/keystone-xl-transcanada-pipeline-calgary-support-contracts-oil-alberta-1.4492795|title=Keystone XL pipeline has strong commercial support, TransCanada says|work=CBC News|access-date=2018-03-13|language=en}}</ref>\n*'''Grand Rapids (460&nbsp;km)''' Transports crude oil from the producing area northwest of Fort McMurray, Alberta, to the Edmonton/Heartland, Alberta market region. In October 2012, TransCanada formed a 50\u201350 CAD$3bn joint-venture with Phoenix Energy Holdings Ltd. (the Canadian subsidiary of [[PetroChina]]) to develop the 500&nbsp;km Grand Rapids Pipeline.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/finance/stocks/TRP/key-developments/article/2631892|title=${Instrument_CompanyName} ${Instrument_Ric}  Key Developments|author=Reuters staff|website=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=6 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Energy===\n[[File:Bruce-Nuclear-Szmurlo.jpg|right|thumb|[[Bruce Nuclear Generating Station]]]]\nTC Energy's Energy division consists of power generation and unregulated natural gas storage assets. The power business consists of approximately 7,000 megawatts (MW) of generation capacity owned or under development. These assets are located primarily in Canada and are powered by natural gas, nuclear, and wind.<ref name=\"2018 Annual Report\"/>\n*'''Western Power''' These assets include approximately 1,000 MW of power generation capacity through four natural gas-fired cogeneration facilities in Alberta and one in Arizona.\n*'''Eastern Power''' These assets include approximately 2,900 MW of power generation capacity in Eastern Canada.\n*'''[[Bruce Power]]''' This operates the [[Bruce Nuclear Generating Station]] in Ontario. Comprising eight nuclear units with a combined capacity of approximately 6,400 MW, it is currently the largest operating nuclear power plant in the world. TC Energy holds a 48.4% interest in the asset.\n\n==Ownership==\nAs of February 2020, the bulk of the share capital of TC Energy is owned by 488 [[institutional investors]], who compose 62% of the stock. The dominant shareholder is the [[Royal Bank of Canada]], which owns a fraction over 8% of the company. The [[Big Five (banks)]] together own more than 17% of the outstanding share capital. Significant holdings accrue to the [[Caisse de d\u00e9p\u00f4t et placement du Qu\u00e9bec]] and the [[OMERS]].<ref name=\"nasdaq\">{{cite web |title=TRP TC Energy Corporation Common Stock |url=https://www.nasdaq.com/market-activity/stocks/trp/institutional-holdings |publisher=Nasdaq, Inc.}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\n===Keystone XL Pipeline===\n{{Main|Keystone XL Pipeline}}\n\nTC Energy first proposed the Keystone XL pipeline in 2008.<ref name=downstream4>{{cite news | url = http://www.downstreamtoday.com/news/article.aspx?a_id=11336 | title = TransCanada Proposes Second Oil Pipeline | newspaper = Lincoln Journal-Star | publisher = Downstream Today | first = Art | last = Hovey | date = 2008-06-12 | accessdate = 2008-07-18}}</ref> The proposal faced widespread grassroots opposition with tactics including tree sits in the path of the pipeline<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/business/article/Protesters-in-Texas-climb-trees-to-block-pipeline-3891002.php |title=Protesters in Texas climb trees to block pipeline work |publisher=Houston Chronicle |date=September 25, 2012}}</ref> and civil disobedience by celebrities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.suntimes.com/news/nation/15598994-418/daryl-hannah-freed-following-arrest-in-pipeline-protest.html |title=Daryl Hannah freed following arrest in pipeline protest |publisher=Chicago Sun-Times |date=Oct 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe Keystone XL Pipeline would transport 830,000 barrels of oil per day from the [[Athabasca oil sands]] to [[Steele City, Nebraska]], upon completion. Critics{{who|date=October 2018}} state that by developing the oil sands, fossil fuels will be readily available and the trend toward warming of the atmosphere won't be curbed.{{citation needed|date=October 2018}} The fate of the pipeline is therefore held up as symbolic of America's energy future.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-30103078|title=Why is the Keystone XL pipeline so disputed?|date=2017|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-03-15|language=en-GB}}</ref> Critics{{who|date=October 2018}} have raised concerns about the risks of spillage, as the [[Sandhills (Nebraska)|Sandhills]] region of Nebraska is a fragile ecosystem.{{citation needed|date=October 2018}}\n\nAfter four years of organizing by those opposed to the Keystone XL, the administration of U.S. President Obama rejected the pipeline on November 3, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kerry|first1=John|title=Department of State: Record of Decision and National Interest Determination|url=http://keystonepipeline-xl.state.gov/documents/organization/249450.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151121145230/http://keystonepipeline-xl.state.gov/documents/organization/249450.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=21 November 2015|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Whitehouse|first1=Obama|title=Obama rejects TransCanada's Keystone XL pipeline|url=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/the-press-office/2015/11/06/statement-president-keystone-xl-pipeline|accessdate=6 November 2015|publisher=Whitehouse|date=6 November 2015}}</ref> Early in his tenure in 2017, President [[Donald Trump]] signed presidential memoranda to revive both Keystone XL and [[Dakota Access Pipeline|Dakota Access]] pipelines. The order would expedite the environmental review that Trump described as an \"incredibly cumbersome, long, horrible permitting process\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Mufson |first=Steven |date=January 24, 2017 |title=Trump seeks to revive Dakota Access, Keystone XL oil pipelines |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2017/01/24/trump-gives-green-light-to-dakota-access-keystone-xl-oil-pipelines/ |newspaper=[[Washington Post]] |location=Washington, DC |access-date=January 24, 2017}}</ref> Subsequently, Donald Trump signed a presidential permit to allow TransCanada to build the Keystone XL pipeline on March 24, 2017.<ref name=\"guardian-24mar2017\">{{cite news|last1=Jamieson|first1=Amber|last2=Vaughan|first2=Adam|title=Keystone XL: Trump issues permit to begin construction of pipeline|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/mar/24/keystone-xl-pipeline-permit-trump-administration|accessdate=March 24, 2017|newspaper=The Guardian|date=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThis action by Trump inspired another wave of protests and rallies against the pipeline.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://calgaryherald.com/business/energy/keystone-xl-hundreds-protest-at-white-house-signalling-upcoming-pipeline-fight|title=Keystone XL: Hundreds protest at White House, signalling upcoming pipeline fight|date=2017-01-25|work=Calgary Herald|access-date=2018-03-15|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===Use of eminent domain===\nIn October 2011, TransCanada was involved in up to 56 separate [[eminent domain]] actions against landowners in Texas and South Dakota who refused to give permission to the company to build the [[Keystone Pipeline]] through their land.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/10/18/us/transcanada-in-eminent-domain-fight-over-pipeline.html |title=Eminent Domain Fight Has a Canadian Twist |publisher=New York Times |date=Oct 17, 2011}}</ref> However, on August 23, 2012, Texas Judge Bill Harris ruled that TransCanada had the right of eminent domain and could lease or purchase land from owners who refused to sign an agreement with the company for a public [[right of way]] for the pipeline.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}} The landowners had said that the pipeline was not open to other companies, and so did not meet the criteria for eminent domain.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/texas-judge-rules-in-favor-of-transcanada-in-eminent-domain-case/2012/08/23/87744776-ecda-11e1-a80b-9f898562d010_story.html |title=Keystone pipeline clears a hurdle |publisher=Washington Post |date=Aug 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\nFor several years in 2014-2017 as TransCanada was acquiring Columbia Gas Transmission, dozens of private properties were occupied by their natural gas MB Line construction in Baltimore and Harford County Maryland using hired armed State of Maryland Transit Police and Baltimore City policeman.  .\n\n==Spills==\n\nThe [[Keystone Pipeline]] has had three significant leaks since it opened in 2010. It has leaked approximately 400 barrels in North Dakota in 2011 and South Dakota in 2016, and approximately 5000 barrels in South Dakota in 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-pipeline-keystone-spills/keystones-existing-pipeline-spills-far-more-than-predicted-to-regulators-idUSKBN1DR1CS|title=Keystone's existing pipeline spills far more than predicted to...|date= 2017-11-27|work=Reuters|accessdate=2018-03-15}}</ref>\n\n===Marshall County, South Dakota leak 2017===\n\nOn November 16, 2017, [[oil leak]]ed from the pipeline in [[Marshall County, South Dakota]], for 15 minutes before the flow of oil could be stopped. The company reported the amount as over 210,000 gallons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ksfy.com/content/news/Crews-cleaning-up-Keystone-Pipeline-leak-in-Marshall-County-458046943.html|title=Crews cleaning up Keystone Pipeline leak in Marshall County|publisher=KSFY ABC|date=November 16, 2017|accessdate=November 16, 2017}}</ref> TransCanada reported it discovered the leak in [[Amherst, South Dakota]], at 6 am on Thursday after systems detected a drop in pressure in the northern leg of the pipeline.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-transcanada-keystone-spill/transcanadas-keystone-pipeline-shut-after-5000-barrel-leak-in-u-s-idUSKBN1DG30K|title=TransCanada's Keystone pipeline shut after 5,000-barrel leak in U.S.|publisher=Reuters|date=November 16, 2017|accessdate=November 16, 2017}}</ref> The leak was discovered about 35 miles south of the Ludden pump station.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://heavy.com/news/2017/11/keystone-pipeline-leak-oil-spill-photos/|title=Keystone Pipeline Leak: More Than 200,000 Gallons of Oil Spilled|publisher=Heavy.com|date=November 16, 2017|accessdate=November 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, a federal investigation showed that the spill was almost twice as large as TransCanada had claimed in November, and that it was the seventh-largest onshore oil spill since 2002. The study showed that 407,000 gallons, not 210,000 gallons, had spilled.<ref name=\"VICE\">[https://news.vice.com/en_us/article/evqqmk/egypts-jon-stewart-watched-the-egyptian-elections-from-la \"The Keystone Pipeline oil spill was nearly twice as big as TransCanada said\"], ''[[Vice News]]'', Sarah Sax, April 10, 2018</ref> Also in April 2018, ''[[Reuters]]'' reviewed documents that showed that Keystone had \"leaked substantially more oil, and more often, in the United States than the company indicated to regulators in risk assessments before operations began in 2010\".<ref name=\"DOUBLE\">[https://mobile.reuters.com/article/amp/idUSKBN1HE0T7 \"Keystone pipeline leak in South Dakota about double previous estimate: paper\"], Reuters, April 7, 2018</ref>\n\n==Operational projects==\n===Operational natural gas pipelines===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n! width=\"15%\" | Name\n! width=\"5%\" |Country\n! width=\"10%\" |Length\n! width=\"2.5%\" |TransCa